WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:12.788 --> 00:00:14.050
So this is my niece.
这是我的侄女。

2
00:00:14.464 --> 00:00:15.999
Her name is Yahli.
她叫Yahl。

3
00:00:16.023 --> 00:00:17.534
She is nine months old.
她只有九个月大。

4
00:00:18.021 --> 00:00:20.549
Her mum is a doctor, and her dad is a lawyer.
她妈妈是一名医生， 爸爸是一名律师。

5
00:00:21.089 --> 00:00:23.095
By the time Yahli goes to college,
等到Yahli上大学的时候，

6
00:00:23.119 --> 00:00:26.372
the jobs her parents do are going to look dramatically different.
像她父母这样的工作将面目全非。

7
00:00:27.167 --> 00:00:32.240
In 2013, researchers at Oxford University did a study on the future of work.
2013年，牛津大学的研究人员 做了一项关于未来就业的研究。

8
00:00:32.586 --> 00:00:36.725
They concluded that almost one in every two jobs have a high risk
他们得出结论：差不多将近 一半的工作都有被机器

9
00:00:36.749 --> 00:00:38.573
of being automated by machines.
自动化取代的危险。

10
00:00:40.208 --> 00:00:42.113
Machine learning is the technology
而机器学习

11
00:00:42.137 --> 00:00:44.415
that's responsible for most of this disruption.
应对这种颠覆负主要责任。

12
00:00:44.439 --> 00:00:47.229
It's the most powerful branch of artificial intelligence.
它是人工智能最强大的分支。

13
00:00:47.253 --> 00:00:49.135
It allows machines to learn from data
允许机器从现有数据中学习，

14
00:00:49.159 --> 00:00:51.751
and mimic some of the things that humans can do.
并模仿人类的所作所为。

15
00:00:51.775 --> 00:00:55.190
My company, Kaggle, operates on the cutting edge of machine learning.
我的公司Kaggle 专注于尖端的机器学习。

16
00:00:55.214 --> 00:00:57.600
We bring together hundreds of thousands of experts
我们召集了成千上万的专家

17
00:00:57.624 --> 00:01:00.742
to solve important problems for industry and academia.
正为工业和学术界  寻找重要问题的答案。

18
00:01:01.099 --> 00:01:04.321
This gives us a unique perspective on what machines can do,
因此，我们可以从独特的视角来观察，

19
00:01:04.345 --> 00:01:05.580
what they can't do
机器可以做什么，不可以做什么，

20
00:01:05.604 --> 00:01:08.543
and what jobs they might automate or threaten.
哪些工作可以被自动化或受到威胁。

21
00:01:09.136 --> 00:01:12.686
Machine learning started making its way into industry in the early '90s.
机器学习是在90年代初 进入人们的视野。

22
00:01:12.710 --> 00:01:14.834
It started with relatively simple tasks.
一开始，它只是执行 一些相对简单的任务。

23
00:01:15.226 --> 00:01:19.341
It started with things like assessing credit risk from loan applications,
像评估贷款申请的信用风险，

24
00:01:19.365 --> 00:01:23.418
sorting the mail by reading handwritten characters from zip codes.
通过识别手写的邮政编码来检索邮件。

25
00:01:23.856 --> 00:01:27.025
Over the past few years, we have made dramatic breakthroughs.
在过去几年里，我们取得了突破性进展。

26
00:01:27.406 --> 00:01:31.322
Machine learning is now capable of far, far more complex tasks.
现在，机器学习可以 完成非常复杂的任务。

27
00:01:31.680 --> 00:01:34.911
In 2012, Kaggle challenged its community
2012年，Kaggle给当地学校出了个难题，

28
00:01:34.935 --> 00:01:38.124
to build an algorithm that could grade high-school essays.
设计一个算法来评判高中作文。

29
00:01:38.148 --> 00:01:40.752
The winning algorithms were able to match the grades
获胜的算法给出的分数居然

30
00:01:40.776 --> 00:01:42.441
given by human teachers.
和真正老师给出的分数相符。

31
00:01:42.912 --> 00:01:45.896
Last year, we issued an even more difficult challenge.
去年，我们出了一道更难的题。

32
00:01:45.920 --> 00:01:48.873
Can you take images of the eye and diagnose an eye disease
你能从拍摄出的眼睛图像中 诊断出糖尿病性

33
00:01:48.897 --> 00:01:50.591
called diabetic retinopathy?
视网膜病变吗？

34
00:01:50.984 --> 00:01:55.024
Again, the winning algorithms were able to match the diagnoses
再一次，获胜的演算法给出的诊断

35
00:01:55.048 --> 00:01:56.873
given by human ophthalmologists.
和眼科医生的诊断相符。

36
00:01:57.381 --> 00:02:00.593
Now, given the right data, machines are going to outperform humans
类似于这样的任务， 只要给定正确的数据，

37
00:02:00.617 --> 00:02:01.782
at tasks like this.
机器将完全超越人类。

38
00:02:01.806 --> 00:02:05.798
A teacher might read 10,000 essays over a 40-year career.
一位老师在40年的职业生涯中 可能审阅一万篇作文。

39
00:02:06.227 --> 00:02:08.587
An ophthalmologist might see 50,000 eyes.
一名眼科医生，大概可以检查 5万只眼睛。

40
00:02:08.611 --> 00:02:12.524
A machine can read millions of essays or see millions of eyes
但在短短几分钟之内， 机器可以审阅百万篇文章

41
00:02:12.548 --> 00:02:13.824
within minutes.
或检查数百万只眼睛。

42
00:02:14.276 --> 00:02:17.134
We have no chance of competing against machines
对于频繁，大批量的任务

43
00:02:17.158 --> 00:02:19.479
on frequent, high-volume tasks.
我们无法与机器抗衡。

44
00:02:20.485 --> 00:02:24.209
But there are things we can do that machines can't do.
但有些事情机器却无能为力。

45
00:02:24.611 --> 00:02:26.811
Where machines have made very little progress
机器在解决新情况方面

46
00:02:26.835 --> 00:02:28.689
is in tackling novel situations.
进展甚微。

47
00:02:28.713 --> 00:02:32.612
They can't handle things they haven't seen many times before.
它们还不能处理未曾反复接触的事情。

48
00:02:33.141 --> 00:02:35.725
The fundamental limitations of machine learning
机器学习致命的局限性在于

49
00:02:35.749 --> 00:02:39.143
is that it needs to learn from large volumes of past data.
它需要从大量已知的数据中总结经验。

50
00:02:39.167 --> 00:02:40.921
Now, humans don't.
人类则不然。

51
00:02:40.945 --> 00:02:43.975
We have the ability to connect seemingly disparate threads
我们有一种能把看似毫不相关的事物 联系起来的能力，

52
00:02:43.999 --> 00:02:46.237
to solve problems we've never seen before.
从而解决从未见过的问题

53
00:02:46.628 --> 00:02:51.039
Percy Spencer was a physicist working on radar during World War II,
Percy Spencer是一个物理学家， 在二战期间从事雷达的研究工作，

54
00:02:51.063 --> 00:02:54.076
when he noticed the magnetron was melting his chocolate bar.
他注意到磁控管融化了他的巧克力。

55
00:02:54.790 --> 00:02:58.085
He was able to connect his understanding of electromagnetic radiation
他从对电磁辐射的理解

56
00:02:58.109 --> 00:02:59.593
with his knowledge of cooking
联想到烹饪，

57
00:02:59.617 --> 00:03:02.875
in order to invent -- any guesses? -- the microwave oven.
因此发明了——猜猜是什么？—— 微波炉。

58
00:03:03.264 --> 00:03:06.337
Now, this is a particularly remarkable example of creativity.
这是个非常杰出的创新例子。

59
00:03:06.361 --> 00:03:10.025
But this sort of cross-pollination happens for each of us in small ways
但这种跨界转型，每天正以 难以察觉的方式在我们身边

60
00:03:10.049 --> 00:03:11.877
thousands of times per day.
发生成千上百次。

61
00:03:12.321 --> 00:03:13.982
Machines cannot compete with us
在创新方面

62
00:03:14.006 --> 00:03:16.257
when it comes to tackling novel situations,
机器无法与我们抗衡。

63
00:03:16.281 --> 00:03:19.398
and this puts a fundamental limit on the human tasks
这将使机器自动化取代人工

64
00:03:19.422 --> 00:03:21.139
that machines will automate.
受到限制。

65
00:03:21.861 --> 00:03:24.266
So what does this mean for the future of work?
那么这对未来的工作意味着什么呢？

66
00:03:24.624 --> 00:03:29.156
The future state of any single job lies in the answer to a single question:
未来工作的状态 完全取决于一个问题：

67
00:03:29.180 --> 00:03:34.161
To what extent is that job reducible to frequent, high-volume tasks,
这种工作在多大程度上可以简化为 频繁，大批量的任务，

68
00:03:34.185 --> 00:03:37.438
and to what extent does it involve tackling novel situations?
又涉及多少对创新能力的要求？

69
00:03:37.795 --> 00:03:41.830
On frequent, high-volume tasks, machines are getting smarter and smarter.
对于那些频繁，大批量的任务， 机器变得越来越智能。

70
00:03:41.854 --> 00:03:44.568
Today they grade essays. They diagnose certain diseases.
如今， 它们可以评判作文， 诊断某些疾病。

71
00:03:44.592 --> 00:03:47.749
Over coming years, they're going to conduct our audits,
再过几年，它们将可以进行审计，

72
00:03:47.773 --> 00:03:50.740
and they're going to read boilerplate from legal contracts.
将能审阅法律合同样本。

73
00:03:50.764 --> 00:03:52.761
Accountants and lawyers are still needed.
尽管会计师和律师还是需要的。

74
00:03:52.785 --> 00:03:55.467
They're going to be needed for complex tax structuring,
但他们只需要研究复杂的税收结构，

75
00:03:55.491 --> 00:03:56.848
for pathbreaking litigation.
或无先例的诉讼过程。

76
00:03:56.872 --> 00:03:58.589
But machines will shrink their ranks
但机器将会挤占他们的位置，

77
00:03:58.613 --> 00:04:00.485
and make these jobs harder to come by.
增加就业难度。

78
00:04:00.509 --> 00:04:01.660
Now, as mentioned,
如上所述，

79
00:04:01.684 --> 00:04:04.633
machines are not making progress on novel situations.
在创新方面机器没有取得太大进展。

80
00:04:04.657 --> 00:04:08.114
The copy behind a marketing campaign needs to grab consumers' attention.
营销文案需要抓住消费者的心理。

81
00:04:08.138 --> 00:04:09.853
It has to stand out from the crowd.
脱颖而出是关键。

82
00:04:09.877 --> 00:04:12.321
Business strategy means finding gaps in the market,
商业策略需要找到市场上

83
00:04:12.345 --> 00:04:14.101
things that nobody else is doing.
还无人问津的空白。

84
00:04:14.125 --> 00:04:18.243
It will be humans that are creating the copy behind our marketing campaigns,
人类将是营销文案的创造者，

85
00:04:18.267 --> 00:04:21.784
and it will be humans that are developing our business strategy.
人类才能推动商业战略发展。

86
00:04:21.808 --> 00:04:24.625
So Yahli, whatever you decide to do,
所以Yahli，无论你将来决定做什么，

87
00:04:24.649 --> 00:04:27.010
let every day bring you a new challenge.
让每一天都带给你新的挑战。

88
00:04:27.407 --> 00:04:30.216
If it does, then you will stay ahead of the machines.
如果是那样， 你的未来将无法被机器取代。

89
00:04:30.946 --> 00:04:32.122
Thank you.
谢谢。

90
00:04:32.146 --> 00:04:35.250
(Applause)
（掌声 ）